Juan Maldacena – "Some thoughts on the wave function of the universe" (Strings 2002, Cambridge)

WAVE FUNCTION IN STRING THEORY
M-theory is a quantum gravity theory, so it must contain a wave function of the universe.
In AdS/CFT this is concrete: the boundary CFT has a Hilbert space and wave function.
On the gravity side, the semiclassical Wheeler–DeWitt wave function depends on all
possible spatial slices. Its oscillatory phase encodes how slices patch together to
reconstruct bulk geometry. The scale factor plays the role of time.

HILBERT SPACE LIVES ON THE BOUNDARY
The Hilbert space is that of the boundary CFT. Multiple boundaries → tensor product.
Bulk Hamiltonian = 0; boundary Hamiltonian ≠ 0 and generates time evolution. Black hole
singularity information is encoded in boundary data. There is no evidence for a bulk
interior Hilbert space independent of the boundary. Analogous to Chern–Simons theory:
topological bulk, degrees of freedom only appear when boundaries are introduced.

EUCLIDEAN QG & GKPW PRESCRIPTION
Hartle–Hawking: wave function is oscillatory in some regions, exponentially decaying in
others. Euclidean QG computes the exponentially suppressed tail. The GKPW relation
equates the wave function on a large spatial slice with the CFT partition function on
that geometry, regulated by cutoff ε. For scales ≫ ε the answer is universal. We know
a lot about very improbable configurations; the interesting ones are the most probable.

DE SITTER & INFLATION
The most probable configurations are in the oscillatory (de Sitter) regime. The early
universe during inflation is approximately de Sitter. Measuring primordial fluctuations
at the end of inflation = measuring the Hartle–Hawking wave function. The subsequent
universe acts as a measurement apparatus; we are meta-observers of that quantum state.

TWO-POINT FUNCTIONS & NON-GAUSSIANITY
Graviton 2-pt function ∝ 1/c (c = central charge of dual CFT), enhanced by slow-roll.
Scalar fluctuations correspond to the trace of the stress tensor 2-pt function; in an
exactly conformal theory this trace vanishes, but slow-roll breaking makes it small.
The 1/c vs c relation comes from integrating: the CFT 2-pt function gives the Gaussian
coefficient in the wave function, and computing the variance inverts it. Non-Gaussianity:
expand Einstein action to cubic order. Leading correction ~ H/M_Pl, further suppressed
by slow-roll. Cosmic variance makes it unmeasurable.

FINITE HILBERT SPACE IN DE SITTER?
De Sitter entropy S_dS interpreted as log(dim Hilbert space).
Conservative view: S counts states an observer can measure; entropy = entanglement
between accessible and complementary regions.
Radical view (Banks–Fischler): S is the TOTAL Hilbert space dimension.
In the early universe S > 10^12. Standard inflation treats a huge number of independent
modes. In the radical view they should not all be independent, but with one universe
and cosmic variance, sharp tests are nearly impossible. Maldacena flips the usual
analogy: uses the eternal black hole (two independent Hilbert spaces, one per side) to
argue de Sitter has dim ~ e^{S_dS} per Hubble volume, growing to infinite total dim.

WORMHOLES IN STRING THEORY
No Lorentzian wormhole connecting two asymptotically flat regions is known in string
theory. In AdS, the Witten–Yau theorem forbids wormholes for positive-curvature
boundaries. Negative-curvature boundaries in N=4 YM destabilize via conformal scalar
coupling. But in AdS₃ / 2d CFT, negative curvature is harmless (CFT on a Riemann
surface), and wormhole spacetimes with two asymptotic regions exist. Puzzle: Euclidean
wave function on two disconnected boundaries, yet bulk is connected → correlations.
In de Sitter: two sides of the Penrose diagram are connected. The Hartle–Hawking
prescription (gluing a Euclidean hemisphere) provides the non-singular initial condition;
perturbation theory is well-defined on it. Alpha vacua lack such a prescription.

BLACK HOLE UNITARITY & THE FINAL STATE PROPOSAL
"The most speculative part." Standard Hawking: quantize scalar on BH background.
Hilbert space = interior ⊗ exterior. Vacuum evolves to entangled state Σ|i⟩_in⊗|i⟩_out.
Tracing over interior → thermal density matrix → information loss.

Horowitz–Maldacena proposal: impose a unique final state |BH⟩ at the future singularity.
The singularity is spacelike; the interior evolves to a single fixed state. Outgoing
state = ⟨BH|Ψ_entangled⟩. The state |BH⟩ encodes a unitary operator relating infalling
and interior degrees of freedom. Averaging over many final states recovers thermal answer.

On acausality: infalling observer is localized at wavelengths ≪ horizon; Hawking
radiation has wavelengths ~ horizon. The observer cannot measure infalling Hawking quanta,
so the final boundary condition affects only horizon-scale modes — no observable acausal
effects for the infalling observer. Different infalling matter → different singularity
absorption → different Hawking radiation. Unitarity preserved.

CLOSING REMARKS
A de Sitter observer accesses only a finite-dim Hilbert space C^N but cannot store the
infinite digits needed for a state vector in continuous space. Perhaps in finite systems
the wave function lives on a discrete space — a departure from standard QM.

Q&A HIGHLIGHTS
• On falling in orthogonal to |BH⟩: to arrange orthogonality you'd need to fix yourself
  AND the low-energy infalling Hawking quanta at spacelike separation — not possible.
• Shenker on cosmic variance: gravitational wave detectors at short wavelengths have many
  independent modes, but distinguishing pure vs mixed density matrix (dim N=e^S) requires
  ~N or N² measurements — exponentially impractical when S ~ 10^10. Maldacena agrees. 